# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: signal-integrity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In electronics, **crosstalk** (**XT**) is a phenomenon by which a signal transmitted on one circuit or channel of a transmission system creates an undesired effect in another circuit or channel.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Crosstalk is usually caused by undesired capacitive, inductive, or conductive coupling from one circuit or channel to another.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Where the electric, magnetic, or traveling fields of two electric signals overlap, the electromagnetic interference created causes crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] For example, crosstalk can comprise magnetic fields that induce a smaller signal in neighboring wires.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In electrical circuits sharing a common signal return path, electrical impedance in the return path creates **common impedance coupling** between the signals, resulting in crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Crosstalk is a significant issue in structured cabling, audio electronics, integrated circuit design, wireless communication and other communications systems.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In structured cabling, crosstalk refers to electromagnetic interference from one unshielded twisted pair to another twisted pair, normally running in parallel.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Signals traveling through adjacent pairs of wire create magnetic fields that interact with each other, inducing interference in the neighboring pair.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] The pair causing the interference is called the *disturbing pair*, while the pair experiencing the interference is the *disturbed pair*.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] NEXT is a measure of the ability of a cable to reject crosstalk, so the higher the NEXT value, the greater the rejection of crosstalk at the local connection.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] because the interference between the two signals in the cable is measured at the same end of the cable as the interfering transmitter.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] The NEXT value for a given cable type is generally expressed in decibels per feet or decibels per 1000 feet and varies with the frequency of transmission.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] General specifications for cabling (such as CAT 5) usually include the minimum NEXT values.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] PSNEXT is a NEXT measurement which includes the sum of crosstalk contributions from all adjacent pairs as an algebraic sum of the NEXT of the three wire pairs as they affect the fourth pair in a four-pair cable (e.g., Category 6 cable).
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] states that the testing process for PSNEXT consists of measuring all pair-to-pair crosstalk combinations and then summing all of the values for each pair.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] The specification was developed to directly address the effect of transmissions on multiple adjacent pairs on the pair being tested and is relevant to all connecting hardware and associated communications cables.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] uses all four wire pairs simultaneously and bidirectionally.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] The additional wire pair usage and growing bandwidth increases the need to keep NEXT in check.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] FEXT measures the interference between two pairs of a cable measured at the far end of the cable with respect to the interfering transmitter.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] ELFEXT measures the FEXT with attenuation compensation.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] AXT is interference caused by other cables routed close to the cable of interest as opposed to signals contained in the same cable.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In stereo audio reproduction, crosstalk can refer to signal leakage across from one program channel to another, reducing channel separation and stereo imaging.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Crosstalk between channels in mixing consoles, and between studio feeds is a much more noticeable problem, as these are likely to be carrying very different programs or material.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Crosstalk is an electrical effect and can be quantified with a crosstalk measurement.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Crosstalk measurements are made on audio systems to determine the amount of signal leaking from one channel to another.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] The Independent Broadcasting Authority published a weighting curve for use in crosstalk measurement that gives due emphasis to the subjective audibility of different frequencies.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In the absence of any international standards, this is still in use despite the demise of the IBA.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Good crosstalk performance for a stereo system is not difficult to achieve in today's digital audio systems, though it is difficult to keep below the desired figure of −30 dB or so on vinyl recordings and FM radio.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In telecommunication or telephony, crosstalk is often distinguishable as pieces of speech or in-band signaling tones leaking from other people's connections.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] If the connection is analog, twisted pair cabling can often be used to reduce crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Alternatively, the signals can be converted to digital form, which is typically less susceptible to crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In wireless communication, crosstalk is often denoted co-channel interference, and is related to adjacent-channel interference.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In integrated circuit design, crosstalk normally refers to a signal affecting another nearby signal.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] Usually, the coupling is capacitive, and to the nearest neighbor, but other forms of coupling and effects on signal further away are sometimes important, especially in analog designs.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] See signal integrity for tools used to measure and prevent this problem, and substrate coupling for a discussion of crosstalk conveyed through the integrated circuit substrate.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] There are a wide variety of repair solutions, with increased spacing, wire re-ordering, and shielding being the most common.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In full-field optical coherence tomography, "crosstalk" refers to the phenomenon that due to highly scattering objects, multiple scattered photons reach the image plane and generate a coherent signal after travelling a path length that matches that of the sample depth within a coherence length.
[src:signal-integrity/crosstalk] In stereoscopic 3D displays, crosstalk refers to the incomplete isolation of the left and right image channels so that one bleeds into the other – like a double exposure, which produces a ghosting effect.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In telecommunications, an **eye pattern**, also known as an **eye diagram**, is an oscilloscope display in which a digital signal from a receiver is repetitively sampled and applied to the vertical input (*y-axis*), while the data rate is used to trigger the horizontal sweep (*x-axis*).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] It is so called because, for several types of coding, the pattern looks like a series of eyes between a pair of rails.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] It is a tool for the evaluation of the combined effects of channel noise, dispersion and intersymbol interference on the performance of a baseband pulse-transmission system.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The technique was first used with the WWII SIGSALY secure speech transmission system.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] From a mathematical perspective, an eye pattern is a visualization of the probability density function (PDF) of the signal, modulo the unit interval (UI).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In other words, it shows the probability of the signal being at each possible voltage across the duration of the UI.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Typically, a color ramp is applied to the PDF in order to make small brightness differences easier to visualize.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Several system performance measurements can be derived by analyzing the display.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] If the signals are too long, too short, poorly synchronized with the system clock, too high, too low, too noisy, or too slow to change, or have too much undershoot or overshoot, this can be observed from the eye diagram.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] An open eye pattern corresponds to minimal signal distortion.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Distortion of the signal waveform due to intersymbol interference and noise appears as closure of the eye pattern.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The first step of computing an eye pattern is normally to obtain the waveform being analyzed in a quantized form.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This may be done by measuring an actual electrical system with an oscilloscope of sufficient bandwidth, or by creating synthetic data with a circuit simulator in order to evaluate the signal integrity of a proposed design.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] A combination of the two approaches may be used as well: simulating the effects of an arbitrary circuit or transmission line on a measured signal, perhaps to determine whether a signal will still be intelligible after passing through a long cable.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Interpolation may also be applied at this time in order to increase the number of samples per unit interval (UI) and produce a smooth, gap-free plot which is more visually appealing and easier to understand.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Next, the position of each sample within the UI must be determined.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] There are several methods for doing this, depending on the characteristics of the signal and the capabilities of the oscilloscope and software in use.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This step is critically important for accurate visualization of jitter in the eye.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] A very simple method of slicing is to set the oscilloscope display to be slightly more than one UI wide, trigger on both rising and falling edges in the signal, and enable display persistence so that all measured waveforms "stack" into a single plot.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This has the advantage of being possible on almost any oscilloscope (even fully analog ones) and can provide decent visualization of noise and overall signal shape, but completely destroys the jitter content of the signal since the instrument's trigger resynchronizes the plot to each UI.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The only jitter visible with this method is that of the oscilloscope itself, as well as extremely high-frequency jitter (frequencies with period less than the UI).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] A simple way to have the eye pattern display jitter in the signal is to estimate the symbol rate of the signal (perhaps by counting the average number of zero crossings in a known window of time) and acquiring many UIs in a single oscilloscope capture.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The first zero crossing in the capture is located and declared to be the start of the first UI, and the remainder of the waveform is divided into chunks one UI long.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This approach can work adequately for stable signals in which the symbol rate remains exactly the same over time; however, inaccuracies in the system mean that some drift is inevitable, so it is rarely used in practice.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In some protocols, such as SATA, the symbol rate is intentionally varied by use of spread-spectrum clocking, so assuming a fixed rate will lead to the eye grossly exaggerating the actual jitter present on the signal.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] (While spread spectrum modulation on a clock is technically jitter in the strict sense, receivers for these systems are designed to track the modulation.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] With some protocols, such as HDMI, a reference clock is supplied along with the signal, either at the symbol rate or at a lower (but synchronized) frequency from which a symbol clock can be reconstructed.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Since the actual receiver in the system uses the reference clock to sample the data, using this clock to determine UI boundaries allows the eye pattern to faithfully display the signal as the receiver sees it: only jitter between the signal and the reference clock is displayed.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Most high-speed serial signals, such as PCIe, DisplayPort, and most variants of Ethernet, use a line code which is intended to allow easy clock recovery by means of a PLL.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Since this is how the actual receiver works, the most accurate way to slice data for the eye pattern is to implement a PLL with the same characteristics in software.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Correct PLL configuration allows for the eye to conceal the effects of spread spectrum clocking and other long-term variations in the symbol rate that do not contribute to errors at the receiver, while still displaying higher frequency jitter.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The samples are then accumulated into a two-dimensional histogram, with the X axis representing time within the UI and the Y axis representing voltage.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This is then normalized by dividing the value in each histogram bin by the value in the largest bin.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Tone mapping, logarithmic scaling, or other mathematical transformations may be applied in order to emphasize different portions of the distribution, and a color gradient is applied to the final eye for display.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Large amounts of data may be needed to provide an accurate representation of the signal; tens to hundreds of millions of UIs are frequently used for a single eye pattern.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In the example below, the eye using twelve thousand UIs only shows the basic shape of the eye, while the eye using eight million UIs shows far more nuance on the rising and falling edges.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Each form of baseband modulation produces an eye pattern with a unique appearance.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The eye pattern of a NRZ signal should consist of two clearly distinct levels with smooth transitions between them.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The eye pattern of a MLT-3 signal should consist of three clearly distinct levels (nominally -1, 0, +1 from bottom to top).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The 0 level should be located at zero volts and the overall shape should be symmetric about the horizontal axis.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The +1 and -1 states should have equal amplitude.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] There should be smooth transitions from the 0 state to the +1 and -1 states; however, there should be no direct transitions from the -1 to +1 state (which would indicate the signal is PAM-3 rather than MLT-3).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The eye pattern of a PAM signal should consist of N clearly distinct levels (depending on the PAM order, for example, PAM-4 should have four levels and PAM-3 should have three).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The overall shape should be symmetric about the horizontal axis and the spacing of all levels should be uniform.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Many properties of a channel can be seen in the eye pattern.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Emphasis applied to a signal produces an additional level for each value of the signal, which is higher (for pre-emphasis) or lower (for de-emphasis) than the nominal value.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The eye pattern for a signal with emphasis may be mistaken for that of a PAM signal at first glance; however, closer inspection reveals some key differences.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] An emphasized signal will never transition from a weak state to the corresponding strong state, a weak state to another weak state, or remain in the same strong state for more than one UI.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] A PAM signal also normally has equally spaced levels, while emphasized levels are normally closer to the nominal signal level.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Loss of printed circuit board traces and cables increases with frequency due to dielectric loss, which causes the channel to behave as a low-pass filter.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The effect of this is an increase in signal rise/fall time.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] If the data rate is high enough or the channel is lossy enough, the signal may not even reach its full value during a fast 0–1–0 or 1–0–1 transition, and only stabilize after a run of several identical bits.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This results in vertical closure of the eye.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The image below shows a 1.25 Gbit/s NRZ signal after passing through a lossy channel – an RG-188 coaxial cable approximately 12 feet (3.7 m) in length.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This channel has loss increasing in a fairly linear fashion from 0.1 dB at DC to 9 dB at 6 GHz.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The top and bottom "rails" of the eye show the final voltage the signal reaches after several consecutive bits with the same value.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Since the channel has minimal loss at DC, the maximum signal amplitude is largely unaffected.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Looking at the rising edge of the signal (a 0–1 pattern) we can see that the signal starts to level off around −300 ps, but continues to rise slowly over the duration of the UI.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] At around +300 ps, the signal either begins falling again (a 0–1–0 pattern) or continues rising slowly (a 0–1–1 pattern).
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] As high frequency losses increase, the overall shape of the eye gradually degrades into a sinusoid (once higher frequency harmonics of the data have been eliminated, all that remains is the fundamental) and decreases in amplitude.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Stubs, impedance mismatches, and other defects in a transmission line can cause reflections visible as defects in the edges of the signal.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] Reflections with a delay greater than one UI often render the eye completely unreadable due to inter-symbol interference (ISI); however, those with a shorter delay can be easily seen in the shape of the eye.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In the image below, a roughly 1-inch (25 mm) open-circuited stub is present in the line, causing an initial low-impedance effect (reduced amplitude) followed by a positive reflection from the end of the stub with a delay of about 320 ps or 0.4 UIs.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This can be clearly seen as a "step" in the rising edge in which the signal rises to a fraction of the full value, levels off for the round-trip delay of the stub, then rises to its full value when the reflection arrives.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] In the image below, an additional three inches of cable is added to the end of the same stub.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] The same "step" is present but is now four times as long, producing reflections at about 1280 ps or 1.6 UI.
[src:signal-integrity/eye-pattern] This produces extreme ISI (since the reflection of each UI arrives during the subsequent UI), which completely closes the eye.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In electrical engineering, **impedance matching** is the practice of designing or adjusting the input impedance or output impedance of an electrical device for a desired value.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Often, the desired value is selected to maximize power transfer or minimize signal reflection.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For example, impedance matching typically is used to improve power transfer from a radio transmitter via the interconnecting transmission line to the antenna.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Signals on a transmission line will be transmitted without reflections if the transmission line is terminated with a matching impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Techniques of impedance matching include transformers, adjustable networks of lumped resistance, capacitance and inductance, or properly proportioned transmission lines.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Practical impedance-matching devices will generally provide best results over a specified frequency band.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The concept of impedance matching is widespread in electrical engineering, but is relevant in other applications in which a form of energy, not necessarily electrical, is transferred between a source and a load, such as in acoustics or optics.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Impedance characterizes the ratio of energy components in a given domain.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For constant signals, this impedance can also be constant.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For varying signals, it usually changes with frequency.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The energy involved can be electrical, mechanical, acoustic, magnetic, electromagnetic, or thermal.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The concept of electrical impedance is perhaps the most commonly known.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Electrical impedance, like electrical resistance, is measured in ohms.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In general, impedance (symbol: *Z*) has a complex value; this means that loads generally have a resistance component (symbol: *R*) which forms the real part and a reactance component (symbol: *X*) which forms the imaginary part.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This impedance characterizes the ratio between the voltage and current components in the medium.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In simple cases (such as low-frequency or direct current power transmission) the reactance may be negligible or zero; the impedance can be considered a pure resistance, expressed as a real number.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In the following summary we will consider the general case when resistance and reactance are both significant, and the special case in which the reactance is negligible.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Complex conjugate matching is used when maximum power transfer is required, namely $Z_{\text{load}}=Z_{\text{source}}^{*},$ where a superscript * indicates the complex conjugate.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A conjugate match is different from a reflection-less match when either the source or load has a reactive component.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the source has a reactive component, but the load is purely resistive, then matching can be achieved by adding a reactance of the same magnitude but opposite sign to the load.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This simple matching network, consisting of a single element, will usually achieve a perfect match at only a single frequency.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This is because the added element will either be a capacitor or an inductor, whose impedance in both cases is frequency dependent, and will not, in general, follow the frequency dependence of the source impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For wide bandwidth applications, a more complex network must be designed.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For two impedances to be complex conjugates their resistances must be equal, and their reactances must be equal in magnitude but of opposite signs.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In low-frequency or DC systems (or systems with purely resistive sources and loads) the reactances are zero, or small enough to be ignored.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In this case, maximum power transfer occurs when the resistance of the load is equal to the resistance of the source (see maximum power theorem for a mathematical proof).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Impedance matching is not always necessary.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For example, if delivering a high voltage (to reduce signal degradation or to reduce power consumption) is more important than maximizing power transfer, then *impedance bridging* or *voltage bridging* is often used.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In older audio systems (reliant on transformers and passive filter networks, and based on the telephone system), the source and load resistances were matched at 600 ohms.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] One reason for this was to maximize power transfer, as there were no amplifiers available that could restore lost signal.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Another reason was to ensure correct operation of the hybrid transformers used at central exchange equipment to separate outgoing from incoming speech, so these could be amplified or fed to a four-wire circuit.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Most modern audio circuits, on the other hand, use active amplification and filtering and can use voltage-bridging connections for greatest accuracy.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Strictly speaking, impedance matching only applies when both source and load devices are linear; however, matching may be obtained between nonlinear devices within certain operating ranges.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Adjusting the source impedance or the load impedance, in general, is called "impedance matching".
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] There are a variety of devices used between a source of energy and a load that perform "impedance matching".
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] To match electrical impedances, engineers use combinations of transformers, resistors, inductors, capacitors and transmission lines.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] These passive (and active) impedance-matching devices are optimized for different applications and include baluns, antenna tuners (sometimes called ATUs or roller-coasters, because of their appearance), acoustic horns, matching networks, and terminators.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Transformers are sometimes used to match the impedances of circuits.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A transformer converts alternating current at one voltage to the same waveform at another voltage.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The power input to the transformer and output from the transformer is the same (except for conversion losses).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The side with the lower voltage is at low impedance (because this has the lower number of turns), and the side with the higher voltage is at a higher impedance (as it has more turns in its coil).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] One example of this method involves a television balun transformer.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This transformer allows interfacing a balanced line (300-ohm twin-lead) and an unbalanced line (75-ohm coaxial cable such as RG-6).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] To match the impedances, both cables must be connected to a matching transformer with a turns ratio of 2:1.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In this example, the 300-ohm line is connected to the transformer side with more turns; the 75-ohm cable is connected to the transformer side with fewer turns.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Resistive impedance matches are easiest to design and can be achieved with a simple L pad consisting of two resistors.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Power loss is an unavoidable consequence of using resistive networks, and they are only (usually) used to transfer line level signals.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Most lumped-element devices can match a specific range of load impedances.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For example, in order to match an inductive load into a real impedance, a capacitor needs to be used.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the load impedance becomes capacitive, the matching element must be replaced by an inductor.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In many cases, there is a need to use the same circuit to match a broad range of load impedance and thus simplify the circuit design.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This issue was addressed by the stepped transmission line, where multiple, serially placed, quarter-wave dielectric slugs are used to vary a transmission line's characteristic impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] By controlling the position of each element, a broad range of load impedances can be matched without having to reconnect the circuit.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Filters are frequently used to achieve impedance matching in telecommunications and radio engineering.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In general, it is not theoretically possible to achieve perfect impedance matching at all frequencies with a network of discrete components.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Impedance matching networks are designed with a definite bandwidth, take the form of a filter, and use filter theory in their design.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Applications requiring only a narrow bandwidth, such as radio tuners and transmitters, might use a simple tuned filter such as a stub.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This would provide a perfect match at one specific frequency only.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Wide bandwidth matching requires filters with multiple sections.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A simple electrical impedance-matching network requires one capacitor and one inductor.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In the figure to the right, R1 > R2, however, either R1 or R2 may be the source and the other the load.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] One of X1 or X2 must be an inductor and the other must be a capacitor.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] One reactance is in parallel with the source (or load), and the other is in series with the load (or source).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If a reactance is in parallel *with the source*, the effective network matches from high to low impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Consider a real source impedance of $R_{1}$ and real load impedance of $R_{2}$ .
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Note, $X_{1}$ , the reactance in parallel, has a negative reactance because it is typically a capacitor.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This gives the L-network the additional feature of harmonic suppression since it is a low pass filter too.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The inverse connection (impedance step-up) is simply the reverse—for example, reactance in series with the source.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The magnitude of the impedance ratio is limited by reactance losses such as the Q of the inductor.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Multiple L-sections can be wired in cascade to achieve higher impedance ratios or greater bandwidth.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Transmission line matching networks can be modeled as infinitely many L-sections wired in cascade.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Optimal matching circuits can be designed for a particular system using Smith charts.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Power factor correction devices are intended to cancel the reactive and nonlinear characteristics of a load at the end of a power line.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This causes the load seen by the power line to be purely resistive.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For a given true power required by a load this minimizes the true current supplied through the power lines, and minimizes power wasted in the resistance of those power lines.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For example, a maximum power point tracker is used to extract the maximum power from a solar panel and efficiently transfer it to batteries, the power grid or other loads.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The maximum power theorem applies to its "upstream" connection to the solar panel, so it emulates a load resistance equal to the solar panel source resistance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] However, the maximum power theorem does not apply to its "downstream" connection.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] That connection is an impedance bridging connection; it emulates a high-voltage, low-resistance source to maximize efficiency.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] On the power grid the overall load is usually inductive.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Consequently, power factor correction is most commonly achieved with banks of capacitors.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] It is only necessary for correction to be achieved at one single frequency, the frequency of the supply.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Complex networks are only required when a band of frequencies must be matched and this is the reason why simple capacitors are all that is usually required for power factor correction.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In RF connections, impedance matching is desirable, because otherwise reflections may be created at the end of the mismatched transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The reflection may cause frequency-dependent loss.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In radio-frequency (RF) systems, a common value for source and load impedances is 50 ohms.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A typical RF load is a quarter-wave ground plane antenna (37 ohms with an ideal ground plane).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] so the reflection coefficient is the same (except for sign), no matter from which direction the wave approaches the boundary.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] There is also a current reflection coefficient, which is the negative of the voltage reflection coefficient.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the wave encounters an open at the load end, positive voltage and negative current pulses are transmitted back toward the source (negative current means the current is going the opposite direction).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Thus, at each boundary there are four reflection coefficients (voltage and current on one side, and voltage and current on the other side).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] All four are the same, except that two are positive and two are negative.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The voltage reflection coefficient and current reflection coefficient on the same side have opposite signs.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Voltage reflection coefficients on opposite sides of the boundary have opposite signs.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Because they are all the same except for sign it is traditional to interpret the reflection coefficient as the voltage reflection coefficient (unless otherwise indicated).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Either end (or both ends) of a transmission line can be a source or a load (or both), so there is no inherent preference for which side of the boundary is medium 1 and which side is medium 2.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] With a single transmission line it is customary to define the voltage reflection coefficient for a wave incident on the boundary from the transmission line side, regardless of whether a source or load is connected on the other side.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In a transmission line, a wave travels from the source along the line.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Suppose the wave hits a boundary (an abrupt change in impedance).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Some of the wave is reflected back, while some keeps moving onwards.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is incident on the boundary from the source side.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is transmitted to the load.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] be the voltage and current that is reflected back toward the source.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] where $\Gamma _{TL}\,$ is the reflection coefficient going from the transmission line to the load.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The source of waves incident from the line are the reflections from the load end.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the source impedance matches the line, reflections from the load end will be absorbed at the source end.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the transmission line is not matched at both ends reflections from the load will be re-reflected at the source and re-re-reflected at the load end *ad infinitum*, losing energy on each transit of the transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This can cause a resonance condition and strongly frequency-dependent behavior.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In a narrow-band system this can be desirable for matching, but is generally undesirable in a wide-band system.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] where $T\ ,$ is the one-way transfer function (from either end to the other) when the transmission line is exactly matched at source and load. $T\,$ accounts for everything that happens to the signal in transit (including delay, attenuation and dispersion).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] where $V_{S}\,$ is the open circuit (or unloaded) output voltage from the source.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Telephone systems also use matched impedances to minimise echo on long-distance lines.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This is related to transmission-line theory.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Matching also enables the telephone *hybrid coil* (2- to 4-wire conversion) to operate correctly.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] As the signals are sent and received on the same two-wire circuit to the central office (or exchange), cancellation is necessary at the telephone earpiece so excessive sidetone is not heard.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] All devices used in telephone signal paths are generally dependent on matched cable, source and load impedances.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In the local loop, the impedance chosen is 600 ohms (nominal).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Terminating networks are installed at the exchange to offer the best match to their subscriber lines.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Each country has its own standard for these networks, but they are all designed to approximate about 600 ohms over the voice frequency band.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Audio amplifiers typically do not match impedances, but provide an output impedance that is lower than the load impedance (such as < 0.1 ohm in typical semiconductor amplifiers), for improved speaker damping.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For vacuum tube amplifiers, impedance-changing transformers are often used to get a low output impedance, and to better match the amplifier's performance to the load impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Some tube amplifiers have output transformer taps to adapt the amplifier output to typical loudspeaker impedances.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The impedance of the loudspeaker on the secondary coil of the transformer will be transformed to a higher impedance on the primary coil in the circuit of the power pentodes by the square of the turns ratio, which forms the *impedance scaling factor*.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The output stage in common-drain or common-collector semiconductor-based end stages with MOSFETs or power transistors has a very low output impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If they are properly balanced, there is no need for a transformer or a large electrolytic capacitor to separate AC from DC current.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In NMR techniques (NMR spectroscopy and MR imaging), impedance matching is required to adjust power transfer to the radiofrequency antenna depending on the sample present in the system.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] It is typically performed automatically (in clinical imaging systems for instance) or manually, before acquisitions take place.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The radiofrequency antennas are equipped with variable "match" and "tune" adjusting screws which enable the user or the system to adjust the center frequency and the level of power transfer at the same time.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Similar to electrical transmission lines, an impedance matching problem exists when transferring sound energy from one medium to another.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the acoustic impedance of the two media are very different most sound energy will be reflected (or absorbed), rather than transferred across the border.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The gel used in medical ultrasonography helps transfer acoustic energy from the transducer to the body and back again.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Without the gel, the impedance mismatch in the transducer-to-air and the air-to-body discontinuity reflects almost all the energy, leaving very little to go into the body.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The bones in the middle ear function as a series of levers, which matches mechanical impedance between the eardrum (which is acted upon by vibrations in air) and the fluid-filled inner ear.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Horns in loudspeaker systems are used like transformers in electrical circuits to match the impedance of the transducer to the impedance of the air.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This principle is used in both horn loudspeakers and musical instruments.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Because most driver impedances are poorly matched to the impedance of free air at low frequencies, loudspeaker enclosures are designed to both match impedance and minimize destructive phase cancellations between output from the front and rear of a speaker cone.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The loudness of sound produced in air from a loudspeaker is directly related to the ratio of the diameter of the speaker to the wavelength of the sound being produced: larger speakers can produce lower frequencies at a higher level than smaller speakers.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Elliptical speakers are a complex case, acting like large speakers lengthwise and small speakers crosswise.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Acoustic impedance matching (or the lack of it) affects the operation of a megaphone, an echo and soundproofing.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A similar effect occurs when light (or any electromagnetic wave) hits the interface between two media with different refractive indices.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic materials, the refractive index is inversely proportional to the material's characteristic impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] to calculate reflection and transmission coefficients for the interface.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] For non-magnetic dielectrics, this equation is equivalent to the Fresnel equations.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Unwanted reflections can be reduced by the use of an anti-reflection optical coating.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If a body of mass *m* collides elastically with a second body, maximum energy transfer to the second body will occur when the second body has the same mass *m*.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In a head-on collision of equal masses, the energy of the first body will be completely transferred to the second body (as in Newton's cradle for example).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] In this case, the masses act as "mechanical impedances", which must be matched to maximize energy transfer.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] which is analogous to the power-transfer equation.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If we cannot change the masses of bodies, then we can match their impedance with a lever.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] Imagine a large ball dropping to the ground, and a small ball lying on the ground.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The large ball hits the short end of a lever, and the small ball is launched from the long end of the lever.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If the lever arm lengths satisfy $l_{1}m_{1}=l_{2}m_{2}$ , then all energy would be transferred to the small ball if collisions are elastic.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] This is roughly how the middle ear works (see above).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] These principles are useful in the application of highly energetic materials (explosives).
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] If an explosive charge is placed on a target, the sudden release of energy causes compression waves to propagate through the target radially from the point-charge contact.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] When the compression waves reach areas of high acoustic impedance mismatch (such as the opposite side of the target), tension waves reflect back and create spalling.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] The greater the mismatch, the greater the effect of creasing and spalling will be.
[src:signal-integrity/impedance-matching] A charge initiated against a wall with air behind it will do more damage to the wall than a charge initiated against a wall with soil behind it.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] In telecommunications, **signal reflection** happens when a signal is transmitted along a transmission medium (such as a copper cable or an optical fiber) and part of it is reflected back toward the source instead of reaching the end.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] This reflection is caused by imperfections or physical variations in the cable (such as abrupt changes in its geometry) that lead to impedance mismatches.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] These mismatches disrupt the signal and cause some of it to bounce back.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] In radio frequency (RF) systems, this is typically measured using the voltage standing wave ratio (VSWR), with a device called a VSWR bridge.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] The amount of reflected energy depends on the degree of impedance mismatch and is mathematically described by the reflection coefficient.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] Because the principles are the same, this concept is perhaps easiest to understand when considering an optical fiber.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] Imperfections in the glass create mirrors that reflect the light back along the fiber.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] Impedance discontinuities cause attenuation, attenuation distortion, standing waves, ringing and other effects because a portion of a transmitted signal will be reflected back to the transmitting device rather than continuing to the receiver, much like an echo.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] This effect is compounded if multiple discontinuities cause additional portions of the remaining signal to be reflected back to the transmitter.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] This is a fundamental problem with the daisy chain method of connecting electronic components.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] When a returning reflection strikes another discontinuity, some of the signal rebounds in the original signal direction, creating multiple echo effects.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] These forward echoes strike the receiver at different intervals making it difficult for the receiver to accurately detect data values on the signal.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] The effects can resemble those of jitter.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] Because damage to the cable can cause reflections, an instrument called an electrical time-domain reflectometer (ETDR; for electrical cables) or an optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR; for optical cables) can be used to locate the damaged part of a cable.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] These instruments work by sending a short pulsed signal into the cable and measuring how long the reflection takes to return.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] If only reflection magnitudes are desired, however, and exact fault locations are not required, VSWR bridges perform a similar but lesser function for RF cables.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] The combination of the effects of signal attenuation and impedance discontinuities on a communications link is called insertion loss.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] Proper network operation depends on constant characteristic impedance in all cables and connectors, with no impedance discontinuities in the entire cable system.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] When a sufficient degree of impedance matching is not practical, echo suppressors or echo cancellers, or both, can sometimes reduce the problems.
[src:signal-integrity/reflection-electrical] The Bergeron diagram method, valid for both linear and non-linear models, evaluates the reflection's effects in an electric line.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Some of the **main issues** of concern for signal integrity are ringing, crosstalk, ground bounce, distortion, signal loss, and power supply noise.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Signal integrity primarily involves the electrical performance of the wires and other packaging structures used to move signals about within an electronic product.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Such performance is a matter of basic physics and as such has remained relatively unchanged since the inception of electronic signaling.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The first transatlantic telegraph cable suffered from severe signal integrity problems, and analysis of the problems yielded many of the mathematical tools still used today to analyze signal integrity problems, such as the telegrapher's equations.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Products as old as the Western Electric crossbar telephone exchange (circa 1940), based on the wire-spring relay, suffered almost all the effects seen today - the ringing, crosstalk, ground bounce, and power supply noise that plague modern digital products.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] On printed circuit boards, signal integrity became a serious concern when the transition (rise and fall) times of signals started to become comparable to the propagation time across the board.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Very roughly speaking, this typically happens when system speeds exceed a few tens of MHz.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] At first, only a few of the most important, or highest speed, signals needed detailed analysis or design.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] As speeds increased, a larger and larger fraction of signals needed SI analysis and design practices.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In modern (> 100 MHz) circuit designs, essentially all signals must be designed with SI in mind.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] For ICs, SI analysis became necessary as an effect of reduced design rules.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In the early days of the modern VLSI era, digital chip circuit design and layout were manual processes.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] However, scaling trends (see Moore's law) brought electrical effects back to the forefront in recent technology nodes.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] With scaling of technology below 0.25 μm, the wire delays have become comparable or even greater than the gate delays.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] As a result, the wire delays needed to be considered to achieve timing closure.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In nanometer technologies at 0.13 μm and below, unintended interactions between signals (e.g. crosstalk) became an important consideration for digital design.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] At these technology nodes, the performance and correctness of a design cannot be assured without considering noise effects.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Most of this article is about SI in relation to modern electronic technology - notably the use integrated circuits and printed circuit board technology.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Nevertheless, the principles of SI are not exclusive to the signalling technology used.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] SI existed long before the advent of either technology, and will do so as long as electronic communications persist.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The cost of these failures is very high, and includes photomask costs, engineering costs and opportunity cost due to delayed product introduction.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Therefore, electronic design automation (EDA) tools have been developed to analyze, prevent, and correct these problems.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In integrated circuits, or ICs, the main cause of signal integrity problems is crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In CMOS technologies, this is primarily due to coupling capacitance, but in general it may be caused by mutual inductance, substrate coupling, non-ideal gate operation, and other sources.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The fixes normally involve changing the sizes of drivers and/or spacing of wires.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In analog circuits, designers are also concerned with noise that arise from physical sources, such as thermal noise, flicker noise, and shot noise.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] These noise sources on the one hand present a lower limit to the smallest signal that can be amplified, and on the other, define an upper limit to the useful amplification.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In digital ICs, noise in a signal of interest arises primarily from coupling effects from switching of other signals.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Increasing interconnect density has led to each wire having neighbors that are physically closer together, leading to increased crosstalk between neighboring nets.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] These effects have increased the interactions between signals and decreased the noise immunity of digital CMOS circuits.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] This has led to noise being a significant problem for digital ICs that must be considered by every digital chip designer prior to tape-out.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Modern signal integrity tools for IC design perform all these steps automatically, producing reports that give a design a clean bill of health, or a list of problems that must be fixed.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] However, such tools generally are not applied across an entire IC, but only selected signals of interest.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Once a problem is found, it must be fixed.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Each of these fixes may possibly cause other problems.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] This type of issue must be addressed as part of design flows and design closure.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Re-analysis after design changes is a prudent measure.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] On-die termination (ODT) or Digitally Controlled Impedance (DCI) is the technology where the termination resistor for impedance matching in transmission lines is located within a semiconductor chip, instead of a separate, discrete device mounted on a circuit board.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The closeness of the termination from the receiver shorten the stub between the two, thus improving the overall signal integrity.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] For wired connections, it is important to compare the interconnect flight time to the bit period to decide whether an impedance matched or unmatched connection is needed.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The channel flight time (delay) of the interconnect is roughly 1 ns per 15 cm (6 in) of FR-4 stripline (the propagation velocity depends on the dielectric and the geometry).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Reflections of previous pulses at impedance mismatches die down after a few bounces up and down the line (i.e. on the order of the flight time).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] At low bit rates, the echoes die down on their own, and by midpulse, they are not a concern.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Impedance matching is neither necessary nor desirable.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] There are many circuit board types other than FR-4, but usually they are more costly to manufacture.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The gentle trend to higher bit rates accelerated dramatically in 2004, with the introduction by Intel of the PCI-Express standard.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Examples of mitigation techniques for these impairments are a redesign of the via geometry to ensure an impedance match, use of differential signaling, and preemphasis filtering, respectively.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] At these new multigigabit/s bit rates, the bit period is shorter than the flight time; echoes of previous pulses can arrive at the receiver on top of the main pulse and corrupt it.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In communication engineering this is called intersymbol interference (ISI).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In signal integrity engineering it is usually called eye closure (a reference to the clutter in the center of a type of oscilloscope trace called an eye diagram).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] When the bit period is shorter than the flight time, elimination of reflections using classic microwave techniques like matching the electrical impedance of the transmitter to the interconnect, the sections of interconnect to each other, and the interconnect to the receiver, is crucial.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Termination with a source or load is a synonym for matching at the two ends.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The interconnect impedance that can be selected is constrained by the impedance of free space (~377 Ω), a geometric form factor and by the square root of the relative dielectric constant of the stripline filler (typically FR-4, with a relative dielectric constant of ~4).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Together, these properties determine the trace's characteristic impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] 50 Ω is a convenient choice for single-end lines, and 100 ohm for differential.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] As a consequence of the low impedance required by matching, PCB signal traces carry much more current than their on-chip counterparts.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] This larger current induces crosstalk primarily in a magnetic or inductive mode as opposed to a capacitive mode.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] To combat this crosstalk, digital PCB designers must remain acutely aware of not only the intended signal path for every signal, but also the path of returning signal current for every signal.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The signal itself and its returning signal current path are equally capable of generating inductive crosstalk.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Differential trace pairs help to reduce these effects.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] A third difference between on-chip and chip-to-chip connection involves the cross-sectional size of the signal conductor, namely that PCB conductors are much larger (typically 100 μm or more in width).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Thus, PCB traces have a small series resistance (typically 0.1 Ω/cm) at DC.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The high frequency component of the pulse is however attenuated by additional resistance due to the skin effect and dielectric loss tangent associated with the PCB material.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The main challenge often depends on whether the project is a cost-driven consumer application or a performance-driven infrastructure application.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] They tend to require extensive post-layout verification (using an EM simulator) and pre-layout design optimization (using SPICE and a channel simulator), respectively.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] The noise levels on a trace/network is highly dependent on the routing topology selected.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] In a point-to-point topology, the signal is routed from the transmitter directly to the receiver (this is applied in PCIe, RapidIO, Gigabit Ethernet, DDR2/DDR3/DDR4 DQ/DQS etc.).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] A point-to-point topology has the least SI-problems since there is no large impedance matches being introduced by line T's (a two-way split of a trace).
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] For interfaces where multiple packages are receiving from the same line, (for example with a backplane configuration), the line must be split at some point to service all receivers.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Some stubs and impedance mismatches are deemed to occur.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Multipackage interfaces include BLVDS, DDR2/DDR3/DDR4 C/A bank, RS485 and CAN Bus.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] There are two main multipackage topologies: Tree and fly-by.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] There are special purpose EDA tools that help the engineer perform all these steps on each signal in a design, pointing out problems or verifying the design is ready for manufacture.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Signal Integrity (SI) in PCB design refers to the quality of electrical signals as they travel through traces, vias, and components on a printed circuit board.
[src:signal-integrity/signal-integrity] Ensuring good signal integrity is critical for high-speed and high-frequency designs, as poor signal quality can lead to data errors, signal distortion, and system malfunction.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In electrical engineering, a **transmission line** is a specialized cable or other structure designed to conduct electromagnetic waves in a contained manner.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The term applies when the conductors are long enough that the wave nature of the transmission must be taken into account.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] This applies especially to radio-frequency engineering because the short wavelengths mean that wave phenomena arise over very short distances (this can be as short as millimetres depending on frequency).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] However, the theory of transmission lines was historically developed to explain phenomena on very long telegraph lines, especially submarine telegraph cables.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] RF engineers commonly use short pieces of transmission line, usually in the form of printed planar transmission lines, arranged in certain patterns to build circuits such as filters.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These circuits, known as distributed-element circuits, are an alternative to traditional circuits using discrete capacitors and inductors.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Ordinary electrical cables suffice to carry low frequency alternating current (AC), such as mains power, which reverses direction 100 to 120 times per second, and audio signals.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] However, they are not generally used to carry currents in the radio frequency range, above about 30 kHz, because the energy tends to radiate off the cable as radio waves, causing power losses.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Radio frequency currents also tend to reflect from discontinuities in the cable such as connectors and joints, and travel back down the cable toward the source.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These reflections act as bottlenecks, preventing the signal power from reaching the destination.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Transmission lines use specialized construction, and impedance matching, to carry electromagnetic signals with minimal reflections and power losses.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The distinguishing feature of most transmission lines is that they have uniform cross sectional dimensions along their length, giving them a uniform impedance, called the *characteristic impedance*, to prevent reflections.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Types of transmission line include parallel line (ladder line, twisted pair), coaxial cable, and planar transmission lines such as stripline and microstrip.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The higher the frequency of electromagnetic waves moving through a given cable or medium, the shorter the wavelength of the waves.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Transmission lines become necessary when the transmitted frequency's wavelength is sufficiently short that the length of the cable becomes a significant part of a wavelength.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] At frequencies of microwave and higher, power losses in transmission lines become excessive, and waveguides are used instead, which function as "pipes" to confine and guide the electromagnetic waves.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Some sources define waveguides as a type of transmission line; however, this article will not include them.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Mathematical analysis of the behaviour of electrical transmission lines grew out of the work of James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Oliver Heaviside.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In 1855, Lord Kelvin formulated a diffusion model of the current in a submarine cable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The model correctly predicted the poor performance of the 1858 trans-Atlantic submarine telegraph cable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In 1885, Heaviside published the first papers that described his analysis of propagation in cables and the modern form of the telegrapher's equations.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In the simplest case, the network is assumed to be linear (i.e. the complex voltage across either port is proportional to the complex current flowing into it when there are no reflections), and the two ports are assumed to be interchangeable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Typical values of $Z_{0}$ are 50 or 75 ohms for a coaxial cable, about 100 ohms for a twisted pair of wires, and about 300 ohms for a common type of untwisted pair used in radio transmission.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Propagation delay is proportional to the length of the transmission line and is never less than the length divided by the speed of light.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Typical delays for modern communication transmission lines vary from 3.33 ns/m to 5 ns/m.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] When sending power down a transmission line, it is usually desirable that as much power as possible will be absorbed by the load and as little as possible will be reflected back to the source.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] This can be ensured by making the load impedance equal to $Z_{0}$ , in which case the transmission line is said to be *matched*.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Some of the power that is fed into a transmission line is lost because of its resistance.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] This effect is called *ohmic* or *resistive* loss (see ohmic heating).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] At high frequencies, another effect called *dielectric loss* becomes significant, adding to the losses caused by resistance.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Dielectric loss is caused when the insulating material inside the transmission line absorbs energy from the alternating electric field and converts it to heat (see dielectric heating).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The transmission line is modelled with a resistance ( R ) and inductance ( L ) in series with a capacitance ( C ) and conductance ( G ) in parallel.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The resistance and conductance contribute to the loss in a transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The total loss of power in a transmission line is often specified in decibels per metre (dB/m), and always depends on the frequency of the signal.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The manufacturer often supplies a chart showing the loss in dB/m at a range of frequencies.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A loss of 3 dB corresponds approximately to a halving of the power.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Propagation delay is often specified in units of nanoseconds per metre.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] While propagation delay usually depends on the frequency of the signal, transmission lines are typically operated over frequency ranges where the propagation delay is approximately constant.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The **telegrapher's equations** (or just **telegraph equations**) are a pair of linear differential equations which describe the voltage ( V ) and current ( I ) on an electrical transmission line with distance and time.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] They were developed by Oliver Heaviside who created the *transmission line model*, and are based on Maxwell's equations.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The transmission line model is an example of the distributed-element model.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The model consists of an *infinite series* of the elements shown in the figure, and the values of the components are specified *per unit length* so the picture of the component can be misleading.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] R , L , C , and G may also be functions of frequency.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] An alternative notation is to use $R'$ , $L'$ , $C'$ and $G'$ to emphasize that the values are derivatives with respect to length.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These quantities can also be known as the primary line constants to distinguish from the secondary line constants derived from them, these being the propagation constant, attenuation constant and phase constant.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] When the elements R and G are negligibly small the transmission line is considered as a lossless structure.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In this hypothetical case, the model depends only on the L and C elements which greatly simplifies the analysis.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These are wave equations which have plane waves with equal propagation speed in the forward and reverse directions as solutions.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that electromagnetic waves propagate down transmission lines and in general, there is a reflected component that interferes with the original signal.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These equations are fundamental to transmission line theory.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the (complex) propagation constant.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] They are also wave equations, and have solutions similar to the special case, but which are a mixture of sines and cosines with exponential decay factors.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The constants $V_{(\pm )}$ must be determined from boundary conditions.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] where atan2 is the everywhere-defined form of two-parameter arctangent function, with arbitrary value zero when both arguments are zero.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] with the plus or minus signs chosen opposite to the direction of the wave's motion through the conducting medium.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] If R, G, L, and C are constants that are *not* frequency dependent and the Heaviside condition is met, then waves travel down the transmission line without phase distortion.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ of a transmission line is the ratio of the amplitude of a *single* voltage wave to its current wave.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Since most transmission lines also have a reflected wave, the characteristic impedance is generally not the impedance that is measured on the line.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant and ${\mathit {\Gamma }}_{\mathrm {L} }={\frac {\,Z_{\mathrm {L} }-Z_{0}\,}{Z_{\mathrm {L} }+Z_{0}}}$ is the voltage reflection coefficient measured at the load end of the transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In calculating $\beta ,$ the wavelength is generally different *inside* the transmission line to what it would be in free-space.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Consequently, the velocity factor of the material the transmission line is made of needs to be taken into account when doing such a calculation.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] for all $n\,.$ This includes the case when $n=0$ , meaning that the length of the transmission line is negligibly small compared to the wavelength.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The physical significance of this is that the transmission line can be ignored (i.e. treated as a wire) in either case.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Transmission lines are mainly defined in using ABCD parameters or transmission parameters.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] As $A=D$ , the transmission lines are symmetric networks.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] It also satisfies reciprocity condition $AD-BC=1$ .
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, Y12 = Y21, and Y11 = Y22.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Impedance (Z) parameters are defined by applying a fixed current into one port (I1) of a transmission line with the other port open and measuring the resulting voltage on each port (V1, V2) and computing the impedance parameter Z11 is V1/I1, and the impedance parameter Z12 is V2/I1.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Since transmission lines are electrically passive and symmetric devices, V12 = V21, and V11 = V22.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Unlike ideal lumped 2 port elements (resistors, capacitors, inductors, etc.) which do not have defined Z parameters, transmission lines have an internal path to ground, which permits the definition of Z parameters.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Scattering (S) matrix parameters model the electrical behavior of the transmission line with matched loads at each termination.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] For lossless and lossy transmission lines respectively, the S parameter matrix is as follows, using standard hyperbolic to circular complex translations.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Transmission lines may be placed in proximity to each other such that they electrically interact, such as two microstrip lines in close proximity.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Such transmission lines are said to be coupled transmission lines.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Coupled transmission lines are characterized by an even and odd mode analysis.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The even mode is characterized by excitation of the two conductors with a signal of equal amplitude and phase.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The odd mode is characterized by excitation with signals of equal and opposite magnitude.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The even and odd modes each have their own characteristic impedances ( $Z_{0e}$ , $Z_{0o}$ ) and phase constants ( $\beta _{e}{\text{, }}\beta _{o}$ ).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Lossy coupled transmission lines have their own even and odd mode attenuation constants ( $\alpha _{e}{\text{, }}\alpha _{o}$ ), which in turn leads to even and odd mode propagation constants ( $\gamma _{e}{\text{, }}\gamma _{o}$ ).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Coaxial lines confine virtually all of the electromagnetic wave to the area inside the cable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Coaxial lines can therefore be bent and twisted (subject to limits) without negative effects, and they can be strapped to conductive supports without inducing unwanted currents in them.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] However, at frequencies for which the wavelength (in the dielectric) is significantly shorter than the circumference of the cable other transverse modes can propagate.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These modes are classified into two groups, transverse electric (TE) and transverse magnetic (TM) waveguide modes.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] When more than one mode can exist, bends and other irregularities in the cable geometry can cause power to be transferred from one mode to another.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The most common use for coaxial cables is for television and other signals with bandwidth of multiple megahertz.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In the middle 20th century they carried long distance telephone connections.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Planar transmission lines are transmission lines with conductors, or in some cases dielectric strips, that are flat, ribbon-shaped lines.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] They are used to interconnect components on printed circuits and integrated circuits working at microwave frequencies because the planar type fits in well with the manufacturing methods for these components.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Several forms of planar transmission lines exist.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A microstrip circuit uses a thin flat conductor which is parallel to a ground plane.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Microstrip can be made by having a strip of copper on one side of a printed circuit board (PCB) or ceramic substrate while the other side is a continuous ground plane.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the insulating layer (PCB or ceramic) and the dielectric constant of the insulating layer determine the characteristic impedance.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Microstrip is an open structure whereas coaxial cable is a closed structure.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A stripline circuit uses a flat strip of metal which is sandwiched between two parallel ground planes.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The insulating material of the substrate forms a dielectric.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The width of the strip, the thickness of the substrate and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the strip which is a transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A coplanar waveguide consists of a center strip and two adjacent outer conductors, all three of them flat structures that are deposited onto the same insulating substrate and thus are located in the same plane ("coplanar").
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The width of the center conductor, the distance between inner and outer conductors, and the relative permittivity of the substrate determine the characteristic impedance of the coplanar transmission line.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A balanced line is a transmission line consisting of two conductors of the same type, and equal impedance to ground and other circuits.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] There are many formats of balanced lines, amongst the most common are twisted pair, star quad and twin-lead.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Twisted pairs are commonly used for terrestrial telephone communications.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In such cables, many pairs are grouped together in a single cable, from two to several thousand.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The format is also used for data network distribution inside buildings, but the cable is more expensive because the transmission line parameters are tightly controlled.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Star quad is a four-conductor cable in which all four conductors are twisted together around the cable axis.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] It is sometimes used for two circuits, such as 4-wire telephony and other telecommunications applications.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In this configuration each pair uses two non-adjacent conductors.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Other times it is used for a single, balanced line, such as audio applications and 2-wire telephony.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] In this configuration two non-adjacent conductors are terminated together at both ends of the cable, and the other two conductors are also terminated together.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] When used for two circuits, crosstalk is reduced relative to cables with two separate twisted pairs.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] When used for a single, balanced line, magnetic interference picked up by the cable arrives as a virtually perfect common mode signal, which is easily removed by coupling transformers.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The combined benefits of twisting, balanced signalling, and quadrupole pattern give outstanding noise immunity, especially advantageous for low signal level applications such as microphone cables, even when installed very close to a power cable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The disadvantage is that star quad, in combining two conductors, typically has double the capacitance of similar two-conductor twisted and shielded audio cable.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] High capacitance causes increasing distortion and greater loss of high frequencies as distance increases.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Twin-lead consists of a pair of conductors held apart by a continuous insulator.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] By holding the conductors a known distance apart, the geometry is fixed and the line characteristics are reliably consistent.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] It is lower loss than coaxial cable because the characteristic impedance of twin-lead is generally higher than coaxial cable, leading to lower resistive losses due to the reduced current.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] However, it is more susceptible to interference.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Lecher lines are a form of parallel conductor that can be used at UHF for creating resonant circuits.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] They are a convenient practical format that fills the gap between lumped components (used at HF/VHF) and resonant cavities (used at UHF/SHF).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Unbalanced lines were formerly much used for telegraph transmission, but this form of communication has now fallen into disuse.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Cables are similar to twisted pair in that many cores are bundled into the same cable but only one conductor is provided per circuit and there is no twisting.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] All the circuits on the same route use a common path for the return current (earth return).
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] There is a power transmission version of single-wire earth return in use in many locations.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Electrical transmission lines are very widely used to transmit high frequency signals over long or short distances with minimum power loss.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] One familiar example is the down lead from a TV or radio aerial to the receiver.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A large variety of circuits can also be constructed with transmission lines including impedance matching circuits, filters, power dividers and directional couplers.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A stepped transmission line is used for broad range impedance matching.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] It can be considered as multiple transmission line segments connected in series, with the characteristic impedance of each individual element to be $Z_{\mathrm {0,i} }$ .
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] where $\beta _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the wave number of the $\mathrm {i}$ -th transmission line segment and $\ell _{\mathrm {i} }$ is the length of this segment, and $Z_{\mathrm {i} }$ is the front-end impedance that loads the $\mathrm {i}$ -th segment.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] At higher frequencies, the reactive parasitic effects of real world lumped elements, including inductors and capacitors, limits their usefulness.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Therefore, it is sometimes useful to approximate the electrical characteristics of inductors and capacitors with transmission lines at the higher frequencies using Richards' transformations and then substitute the transmission lines for the lumped elements.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] More accurate forms of multimode high frequency inductor modeling with transmission lines exist for advanced designers.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] If a short-circuited or open-circuited transmission line is wired in parallel with a line used to transfer signals from point A to point B, then it will function as a filter.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The method for making stubs is similar to the method for using Lecher lines for crude frequency measurement, but it is 'working backwards'.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] One method recommended in the RSGB's radiocommunication handbook is to take an open-circuited length of transmission line wired in parallel with the feeder delivering signals from an aerial.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] By cutting the free end of the transmission line, a minimum in the strength of the signal observed at a receiver can be found.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] At this stage the stub filter will reject this frequency and the odd harmonics, but if the free end of the stub is shorted then the stub will become a filter rejecting the even harmonics.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Wideband filters can be achieved using multiple stubs.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] However, this is a somewhat dated technique.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Much more compact filters can be made with other methods such as parallel-line resonators.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] Transmission lines are used as pulse generators.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] By charging the transmission line and then discharging it into a resistive load, a rectangular pulse equal in length to twice the electrical length of the line can be obtained, although with half the voltage.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] A Blumlein transmission line is a related pulse forming device that overcomes this limitation.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] These are sometimes used as the pulsed power sources for radar transmitters and other devices.
[src:signal-integrity/transmission-line] The theory of sound wave propagation is very similar mathematically to that of electromagnetic waves, so techniques from transmission line theory are also used to build structures to conduct acoustic waves; and these are called acoustic transmission lines.
